Events.RelatedBody:
### Description
Currently because of
```
await OnStateChanged();
```
Most of the lifecycle methods inside FormsAppCompatActivity are using async void

This causes any exceptions that are raised in these methods to just be swallowed causing the application to just continue along and eventually crash somewhere else because necessary code never ran

Changing the implementation so these aren't async void would be ideal

### Steps to Reproduce
To reproduce you'd have to manually add an exception into the lifecycle methods.

I came across this because of a different issue that causes Resources to not properly regenerate which leads to the inflation of the Toolbar to fail

```
bar = LayoutInflater.Inflate(ToolbarResource, null).JavaCast<AToolbar>();
```

If that fails then all the code afterwards never runs and then at some random point the app will crash when that initialization code becomes necessary but the root cause has been swallowed

### Expected Behavior
If something throws an exception during the Xamarin Forms life cycle method that exception should not be swallowed or at least be logged in order to give a clear indication of the problem. 

### Actual Behavior
Exception is swallowed

### Implementation Thoughts

At this point the way 
```
OnStateChanged
```
Is executed it's basically fire and forget
There isn't any code that runs afterwards that is dependent on the results of *OnStateChanged* finishing. 

Currently *SendSleepAsync()* is marked as Never Browsable
```
		[EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]
		public Task SendSleepAsync()
		{
			OnSleep();
			return SavePropertiesAsync();
		}
```

If that gives us the latitude to make a slight breaking change then we can create a de-async version of SaveProperties
```
		public async Task SavePropertiesAsync()
		{
			if (Device.IsInvokeRequired)
				Device.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () => await SetPropertiesAsync());
			else
				await SetPropertiesAsync();
		}

		internal async void SaveProperties()
		{
			try
			{
				await SavePropertiesAsync();
			}
			catch(Exception exc)
			{
				Internals.Log.Warning(nameof(Application), $"Failed to Save Properties: {exc}");
			}
		}
```

And then just de-async upwards from there just allowing for a 
```
void OnStateChanged
```

Another possibility would be if there's a safe way where we can ensure no blocking with a call to
```
_application.SendSleepAsync().Wait()
```

I know with Akavache the recommendation is to override life cycle events and then block the lifecycle event until the cache is flushed
